    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nAfter [#39801](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39801), `vim.api.nvim_win_call(win, fn)` returns `nil` instead of `fn`'s return value when invoked from inside a coroutine. Calling it from the main thread still works correctly.\n\nThe new `kRetMultiStack` return mechanism pushes the callback's return values onto a Lua stack, and the dispatch wrapper returns `lua_gettop(lstate)` as the value count. When called from a coroutine, the values appear to land on (or be counted against) the wrong Lua state, so the coroutine's caller sees zero return values.j\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\nlocal co = coroutine.create(function()\n  local curwin = vim.api.nvim_get_current_win()\n  local b = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true)\n  local r = vim.api.nvim_win_call(curwin, function()\n    return vim.api.nvim_open_win(b, false, {\n      relative = \"editor\", width = 10, height = 5, row = 0, col = 0, style = \"minimal\",\n    })\n  end)\n  print(\"result:\", r, type(r))  -- expected: <winid> number ; got: nil nil\nend)\ncoroutine.resume(co)\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`nvim_win_call` should propagate the callback's return value(s) regardless of whether the caller is the main thread or a coroutine.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.13.0-dev-532+g84d5c5f4bf\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS Tahoe 26.3.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty \n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\n`xterm-ghostty`\n\n### Installation\n\nFrom source",
